highlights.description: How LVN conversations are good for the community
Full Highlight about LVN being good for community conversations
Women talking about one year suspension sites in NYC schools and the hearings related to them that are like court proceedings, but parents don't often know they should bring a lawyer
Ramona's story about how her view of criminal justice evolved over her life
"I think this is a really good way where folks can actually have their voice be heard"
"I think it'd be powerful if this stuff was getting played at Albany."

On the normalization of the school to prison pipeline and its implications. --> Update: This is important to listen to because it seems that outside of Milwaukee (in the context of WI) people rarely have these conversations.
On the effects of policy (No Child Left Behind) and its implementation in schools. Students that are suspended are placed in an isolated room from peers completing "educational" requirements.

Students placed in suspension sites are often dealing with more issues than what is seen.  Placing them in suspension sites is not necessarily conducive to learning and does not address the root causes of disruptive behavior (i.e. trauma, poverty, abuse, etc.)    Update: I think people should listen to this because if you did not attend a school with a similar sanctioning mechanism you may have never heard of this more inefficient and inhumane approach to schooling when in reality the youth might just need counseling.

There is an intersectionality between issues of sexual health/violence, homelessness, and the criminal justice system. --> Update:  This is important to listen to because the criminal justice has different effects on different demographics, all vulnerable in their own ways.
Violence was normalized in her childhood community.
Her high school was militarized and inspected youth.
Her memories of visiting a relative in prison.  He served his time and was then deported (i.e. the intersectionality of the criminal justice system and immigration.)
Going to jail is normalized in her community, it is a part of her community's life trajectory.
She experiences points of transition throughout her undergraduate and graduate schooling where she realizes that people from different communities are criminalized differently.

There was internal ethno-racial and ethno-linguistic segregation in her school. --> Update: I thought this was salient in that it shows how students with different needs are divided within schools.  Similarly, students in bilingual classes in schools that I went to were also separated throughout different floors.
Representation matters in decision-making bodies.

On the criteria of the gang database where young people from the ages 13 -24 are disproportionately included and face surveillance. --> Update: I thought this was important as I remember working with immigrant (primarily Latino and Southeast Asian youth) that always talked about their surveillance, especially Muslim youth.
On Muslim community surveillance post 9/11
RIker's Island as the main jail complex in NYC.

Rikers island is not apt to be a prison as its very existence is inhabitable and inhumane. --> Update: I thought this was important to highlight especially given the recent depiction of Rikers on "When They See Us" on the Central Park 5.
The living conditions in prisons (i.e. Rikers and the Barge) are inhumane.
School training students to be in prisons
How the school to prison pipeline was enforced by the No Child Left Behind policy
Emphasizes the ways suspension sites led to more problems i.e. putting kids in the criminal system, kids experiencing more trauma
Defines his role as the facilitator
Althea emphasizes Ramona's experience which prompts a conversation about some of their overlapping experiences, but also acknowledgment that they handled the chaos differently.
